## 1. Introduction & Purpose

The **Copilot Swarm Orchestrator** is a verification-first, multi-agent coordination methodology. It transforms VS Code GitHub Copilot from a single-task assistant into a **parallel, auditable, and self-repairing team of specialists** — operated through disciplined human-in-the-loop orchestration.

Every piece of work generated by an agent is **verified against concrete evidence** before it is merged to the main branch. The orchestrator does not blindly trust the AI. It demands **commit SHAs, test output, and file diffs** as verifiable artifacts of completion.

### What This Is

A **structured methodology** — a set of roles, workflows, prompt templates, and verification checklists — applied consistently across a VS Code Copilot Chat session or series of sessions.

### What This Is Not

- An automated tool or CLI
- A VS Code extension
- A plugin or package you install

The value is in the **discipline**, not the automation. A developer applying this methodology consistently will produce more auditable, higher-quality AI-assisted code than one using Copilot ad hoc.

---

## 2. Core Architectural Principles

| Principle | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Isolation by Branch** | Every agent works in its own git branch (`swarm/<session-id>/step-N-<agent>`). Parallel work never collides, and failures are contained. |
| **Evidence-Based Verification** | Agents must **prove** their work. Claims are cross-checked against `git log`, test output, and `git diff --stat`. No completion is accepted on the AI's word alone. |
| **Human-in-the-Loop Repair** | Failed steps are diagnosed, re-prompted, and re-verified up to 3 times. Verification criteria are **never relaxed** between attempts. |
| **Deterministic Quality Gates** | After merge, eight automated checks use regex, AST analysis, and static thresholds to validate the final codebase. No AI is used here, ensuring reproducibility. |
| **Quota-Aware Scheduling** | Agent mode consumes premium requests. Plan sessions with a step budget and prefer Chat (Ask/Edit) mode for well-scoped tasks to conserve quota. |

---

## 3. System Architecture Overview

The orchestrator is a **conceptual architecture** composed of roles and processes. Understanding each component is essential for applying the methodology correctly.

| Component | Responsibility |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Plan Generator** | Breaks high-level goals into numbered steps, assigns agent roles, and declares inter-step dependencies. Produced via a structured prompt to Copilot or written manually. |
| **PM Agent** | Reviews the plan before execution to catch missing dependencies, circular logic, and undefined done-definitions. Human-invoked. |
| **Step-Executing Agents** | Specialist personas (FrontendExpert, BackendMaster, etc.) invoked one at a time via structured prompts. Each operates in an isolated git branch. |
| **Verification Layer** | A manual checklist applied after each agent turn: git log confirms a commit exists, test output is checked, file diffs are reviewed. |
| **Critic Agent** | Scores completed work on a 100-point rubric. Flags low-scoring steps for human review before merge. |
| **Repair Agent** | A structured re-prompt strategy applied when a step fails verification. Triggered manually; limited to 3 attempts per step. |
| **Quality Gates** | Eight deterministic post-merge checks run as scripts on the final codebase. |
| **Session Log** | A `SESSIONS.md` file maintained by the developer tracking step status, commit SHAs, and transcript locations. |

