## 7. Cost & Quota Management

As of 2025, GitHub Copilot pricing distinguishes between:

- **Base model requests** (unlimited on paid plans, using GPT-4o by default): Standard Copilot Chat and code completions.
- **Premium requests** (quota-limited): Agent mode turns, and Chat turns using premium models (Claude Sonnet, GPT-4.1, o3, etc.).

Agent mode can consume multiple premium requests per prompt because it makes several LLM calls internally as it plans and executes tool calls.

### Planning Principles

| Principle | Guidance |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Reserve Agent Mode for complex, multi-file steps** | For well-scoped, single-file tasks, use Copilot Chat in Edit mode — it is more token-efficient and gives you more direct control. |
| **Set a step budget per session** | Before starting, estimate the number of agent invocations (steps × average repair rate). A rule of thumb: budget 1.5× the number of steps to account for one repair attempt per step on average. |
| **Track quota consumption** | Note in `SESSIONS.md` which steps consumed premium requests and how many turns each agent took. This informs future session planning. |
| **Batch small steps** | If two consecutive steps belong to the same agent and have no parallel dependencies, combine them into a single invocation to reduce per-turn overhead. |
| **Prefer Ask mode for the PM and Critic agents** | These agents read and reason about existing work — they don't need to edit files. Use Chat Ask mode (not Agent mode) for governance agents to conserve quota. |

